Russian Communism Makes a Comeback
More than a year ago, during my sabbatical from teaching at an American university, I returned to my hometown of Moscow.
My destination was not some bastion of free speech.
However, there are still remnants of freedom left in this place.
Opposition leader Alexei Navalny once traveled the country in an attempt to gather support for politicians not under the control of the Kremlin.
Crowd protests erupt.
Independent non-governmental organizations operate domestically.
Journalists and analysts may not necessarily follow the Kremlin's line.
The Communist Party is widely regarded as a historical legacy.
Since then, Navalny has been imprisoned, and the protests he initiated have been suppressed.
Russian anti-corruption foundation is dissolved for "extremism" and its members face exile or investigation.
Almost every day, journalists, media institutions, human rights advocates, or independent organizations are added to the "foreign agents" list, and worse still, are listed as "undesirable".
Russia has plunged into a non-free state in the past year, although not distant, it is extremely intense.
For example, a law was issued in 2012 to designate foreign agents, aimed at destroying or discrediting institutions or citizens who engage in "political activities" and simultaneously receive funding from abroad.
However, the application of this law has become increasingly arbitrary, to the point that forwarding tweets is now a reason to be labeled as a foreign agent.
Those labeled as "undesirable" will face total ban.
This year alone, a record 101 entities were added to the list of foreign agents.
The total number of 359 includes 88 media-related organizations and individuals.
According to the Russian government, the aforementioned "agents" must be listed because they "influence national politics."
Of course, the core goal of news and propaganda work is to influence politics.
It is precisely this that is the problem: despite President Vladimir Putin positioning himself to continue controlling Russian politics in the foreseeable future, he views criticism as a survival threat.
Despite having endured all the silence and persecution, it was the Communist Party that survived and became the only real opposition group in the Kremlin, which is an unlikely group.
This is largely due to Navalny's "smart vote" strategy, which is to encourage the public to support the forces that are most likely to defeat the Kremlin's supported candidates, and the Communist Party demonstrated great strength in both the parliamentary and regional elections last month.
Official data shows that Communist Party candidates won 18.9% of the State Duma (parliamentary) votes, while the United Russia Party, supported by the Kremlin, obtained nearly 49.8%.
However, the Communists refused to acknowledge the results, insisting that the voting results were manipulated.
In fact, some experts estimate that they should have obtained about 30% of the votes, while the United Russia Party should have obtained about 35%.
For many Russians, the communists seem to be more respectable than Putin now.
But they are no longer the original communists.
They not only do not deny the pleasures of the world, but party members are wearing fur coats, enthusiastic about traveling abroad, driving foreign cars, and using social media.
Some of them are millionaires — for example, the attractive head of agriculture, Pavel Grudinin (who was banned from participating in last month's election).
Despite the party still being led by 77-year-old Gennady Zhanayev, it has increasingly been influenced and supported by young party members.
For example, Nikolai Bondarenko.
36-year-old Bondarenko, nicknamed "Red Navalny," severely criticized the pension reform designed in 2018.
A short while ago, a deputy minister said that Russians should be able to live "better" with a monthly salary of just 3,500 rubles (around 50 US dollars), and Bondarenko recorded his efforts to prove this person wrong on his YouTube channel.
Despite being threatened with a ban from running, Bondarenko was still allowed to participate in the recent State Duma elections.
Although he received the support of Navalny's Smart Voting system, he still lost to the United Russia party's candidate.
However, his potential should not be ignored: he recently came up with a title for a protest, accusing "the state and government of taking over" United Russia.
Then there was Anastasia Yudaytsova, 43 years old.
Like Bondarenko, she incredibly lost the last election.
But she still has very — and increasingly — a lot of popularity.
Thanks to the Smart Voting system, another rising star, the elegant Yekaterina Engelhardt, was elected to the Moscow City Duma in 2019.
Ironically, the Communist Party's modernization reform reflected people's nostalgia for the past: in 1917, Lenin's Bolsheviks promised justice and equality, and although the country was strict, it was still not short of justice and kindness.
Furthermore, like the liberal-minded Navalny, today's Communist Party represents a predictable and consistent vision, under which a person's wild imagination would not affect everyone.
Exactly based on this logic, more and more opponents of the Kremlin have joined forces: the "United Russia" (the "United Russia") of the "United Russia" party that can counter Putin.
This is not limited to Russia.
Andrej Babis, also known as the Czech Donald Trump, failed to continue as prime minister in the recent parliamentary election in the Czech Republic because the opposition alliance put aside their ideological differences and formed a joint coalition, which may be led by Petr Fiala who may also lead another opposition alliance to form a new government.
As Fiala said, "People are fed up with populists," they want "normal, competent, and dignified politics."
The Hungarian opposition will also form a unified list for the parliamentary election next year and put forward a unified candidate for prime minister.
Of course, the Czech Republic still maintains a democratic system, so Babis is preparing to join the opposition forces.
However, it would be much more difficult to overthrow Putin, and it's not hard to predict that there will be more comprehensive measures aimed at crushing the communist party.
But the above-mentioned approach also brought risks to the Kremlin.
The current situation is that the president claims that Russian democracy "has not disappeared," and points out that the country still has "an active opposition" as evidence, which indicates that he is at least still interested in pretending not to lead Russia towards a near totalitarian regime.
Putin said he only wants stability.
However, its regime is pushing Russia into a more turbulent situation.
If the Kremlin treats Russian liberals in the same arbitrary way it makes and enforces rules, thereby driving the Communist Party underground, then a social explosion is even more likely to occur.
But if it decides not to suppress it any longer, the Russian Communist people — that's right, the Communist people — could become a force that cannot be ignored.
